    {
      "id": "62584c431103add7882bc14e15a7e1b7129adca7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-06-09 16:08:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nCompatibility with liblustre is not a concern, because it already will refuse to connect if the version is different by +/- 0.3 or so. \n\nWhile I agree that OBD_CONNECT flags can be extended as you suggest, this does add complexity to the client that I would rather avoid if it is not really needed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "894c0e9207cf668f1439b13c151e3d37d6cf736b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-06-10 09:57:37.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 3.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "1d03c2c9ee032e32ab97ac05c6b793b3edf5d646",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-06-10 10:00:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n> Compatibility with liblustre is not a concern, because it already will refuse to connect if the version is different by +/- 0.3 or so.\n\nSeems you misunderstand me. Currently, liblustre client does not support 64-bit dir hash, for both the old 2.0 liblustre client and new 2.1 liblustre client. And 'OBD_CONNECT_64BITHASH' is used for telling the MDS whether the connected client (normal/liblustre) support 64-bit dir hash or not. So means new 2.1 liblustre client does not specify 'OBD_CONNECT_64BITHASH' when connect.\n\nIf we want to redefine 'OBD_CONNECT_SEQ_RANGE' as 'OBD_CONNECT_64BITHASH' to distinguish old 2.0 client or new 2.1 client for fld lookup interoperability issues, that means new 2.1 liblustre client also need to specify 'OBD_CONNECT_SEQ_RANGE', which conflict with above assumption.\n\nSo I have to make some hack: let new 2.1 liblustre client specify 'OBD_CONNECT_SEQ_RANGE' when connect, and it is new 2.1 server's duty to distinguish liblustre and return 32-bit dir hash for it. It works, but breaks the original meanings of 'OBD_CONNECT_64BITHASH'.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "26c6ccb79ce1b3d0a6e0e635daa803d1272c487c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-06-10 10:34:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(4 inline comments)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
